Ritschl, however, in his opposition to the lax theory of previous editors, that Hiatus was adniissible in any circumstances whatever in Plautus, set his face against even this Metrical Hiatus, so far as he could. His views were for a time accepted by his pupils, the editors of the large Teubner edition, so that in their earlier volumes the text has been systematically altered in avoidance of a supposed illegitimate hiatus of this kind. In the small Teubner edition these alterations have been discarded.
